04963nam a22006615i 9783110799514DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022950045  a9783110799514  a(DE-B1597)627081  a(OCoLC)1374540142  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT004130;BISACLIT0240602bisacsh00aReparation, Restitution, and the Politics of Memory / Réparation, restitution et les politiques de la mémoire :bPerspectives from Literary, Historical, and Cultural Studies / Perspectives littéraires, historiques et culturelles /ced. by Mario Laarmann, Clément Ndé Fongang, Carla Seemann, Laura Vordermayer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (IX, 300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeyond Universalism / Partager l'universel : Studies on the Contemporary / Études sur le contemporain ,x2700-1156 ;v30 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aOver the past roughly two decades, the interconnected concepts of reparation, restitution, and commemorative culture have gained renewed momentum - in academic discourse as much as in activist, artistic, and political contexts. This development insists on a critique of the material and systemic conditions of societies and global relations. In their 2018 report on the restitution of looted cultural artifacts, for example, Bénédicte Savoy and Felwine Sarr discuss restitutions in the light of a new ethics of relations. Individual acts of restitution, but also the processes of material and immaterial reparation that go with them, are viewed as mediators in the by definition irreparable legacy of colonialism and its present repercussions. A new ethics of relations might even go beyond anthropocentrism: The destruction of nature in the Anthropocene and the destruction of humanity that is colonialism both require a fundamental questioning of the premises of western modernity and a radically different relationship to the world. The present volume aims to examine different discourses and practices of reparation, bringing together perspectives from cultural studies, memory studies, post- or decolonial studies as well as literary studies. Chapters from these disciplines are complemented by contributions from the fields of philosophy, art, and literature in order to explore the multiple facets of reparation. With contributions by Kader Attia, Lucia della Fontana, Ibou Coulibaly Diop, Alexandre Gefen, Hannah Grimmer, hn. lyonga, Helena Janeczek, Markus Messling, Clément Ndé Fongang, Aurélia Kalisky, Fabiola Obame, Angelica Pesarini, Aurore Reck, Olivier Remaud, Patricia Oster-Stierle, Sahra Rausch, Igiaba Scego, Ibrahima Sene, Christiane Solte-Gresser, Jonas Tinius.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by European Research Council (ERC)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aPostkolonialismus. 4amultidirektionale Erinnerung. 4arelationale Ethik. 4aÖkokritik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 21st Century .2bisacsh  aecocriticism.  amultidirectional memory.  apostcolonialism.  arelational ethics.1 aLaarmann, Mario, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNdé Fongang, Clément, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSeemann, Carla, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVordermayer, Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt2 aEuropean Research Council (ERC)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z